'''Rachel Agatha Keen''' (born 24 October 1997), known professionally as '''Raye''', is a British singer-songwriter. She first rose to prominence after signing with [[Polydor Records]] and subsequently releasing [[Dance music|dance]] singles and [[extended play]]s (EPs). Raye then gained media attention with her departure from the record label, which allegedly refused to release her debut album.

Raye [[Independent music|independently]] released her debut studio album, ''[[My 21st Century Blues]]'' (2023), to critical acclaim. The album's third single, "[[Escapism (Raye song)|Escapism]]", gained popularity in social media and became her first song to top the [[UK singles chart]] and enter the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. At the [[Brit Awards 2024]], Raye won six categories including [[Brit Award for British Artist of the Year|British Artist of the Year]], breaking the record for the artist with the most awards received in a single ceremony of the organization. [[BBC]] included Raye on their ''[[100 Women (BBC)|100 Woman]]'' 2024 list. She received nominations in three categories at the [[67th Annual Grammy Awards]] including [[Grammy Award for Best New Artist|Best New Artist]].

Lyrically focusing on her own struggles and contemporary issues, the majority of Raye's genre-blending music is influenced by [[jazz]], while also incorporating [[Pop music|pop]], [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]], and [[Soul music|soul]]. Outside of [[Raye discography|her own discography]], Raye has co-written songs for other musicians, such as [[Beyoncé]], [[Charli XCX]], [[John Legend]], and [[Little Mix]].

