'''Jaten Collin Dimsdale''' (born September 25, 1992), also known by his stage name '''Teddy Swims''', is an American singer-songwriter and rapper. Known for his genre-blending music, including [[Soul music|soul]], [[Country music|country]], and [[Pop music|pop]], he originally attracted fans through song covers on his [[YouTube]] channel in 2019 and 2020.<ref name="Costa 2020">{{cite web |last=Costa |first=Miguel |date=October 1, 2020 |title=Teddy Swims on His Upcoming Debut EP, Writing Process, and Metamorphosis [Q&A] |url=https://www.onestowatch.com/blog/teddy-swims-on-his-upcoming-debut-ep-writing |access-date=May 2, 2022 |website=Ones to Watch}}</ref> His third extended play, ''Tough Love'' (2022), became his first entry on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]].

Swims rose to prominence in 2023 with the single "[[Lose Control (Teddy Swims song)|Lose Control]]", which peaked within the top ten on the charts in several countries and topped the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] the next year. The song preceded the release of his debut studio album, ''[[I've Tried Everything but Therapy (Part 1)]]'' (2023), which was released by [[Warner Records]] and entered the top ten of music charts in Australia and the Netherlands. In 2024, [[MTV]] named Swims its "Push Artist of February".<ref name="Dresdale 2024 h987">{{cite web |last=Dresdale |first=Andrea |title=Teddy Swims talks "Lose Control," collabs and tattoos for 'MTV PUSH' |website=Y94 |date=February 2, 2024 |url=https://y94.com/2024/02/02/teddy-swims-talks-lose-control-collabs-and-tattoos-for-mtv-push/ |access-date=February 10, 2024}}</ref>

== Early life ==
Swims grew up in [[Conyers, Georgia]]. His father introduced him to soul music at an early age by way of artists like [[Marvin Gaye]], [[Stevie Wonder]], and [[Al Green]].<ref name="Freeman 2021">{{cite magazine |last=Freeman |first=Jon |date=February 5, 2021 |title=The Chameleon Soul of Teddy Swims |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-country/teddy-swims-interview-1122488/ |access-date=May 2, 2022 |magazine=Rolling Stone}}</ref> Swims's family were [[American football]] enthusiasts; he had been playing football for ten years when, during his second year at [[Salem High School (Conyers, Georgia)|Salem High School]], one of his teachers suggested he and a few of his teammates sign up for a musical theater class. The teacher also said he should join the chorus.<ref name="Neunan 2022">{{cite web |last1=Neunan |first1=Megan |title=Singer-songwriter Teddy Swims got his start in Salem High School musicals |url=https://www.rockdalenewtoncitizen.com/news/singer-songwriter-teddy-swims-got-his-start-in-salem-high-school-musicals/article_ff09639a-8f58-11ec-a8bc-d78360a39f5c.html |website=The Citizens |access-date=May 7, 2022 |date=February 18, 2022}}</ref>

Swims discovered his passion for performance through his experience in high-school theater, where he performed in musicals such as ''[[Joseph and the Amazing Technicolor Dreamcoat]]'' and ''[[Rent (musical)|Rent]]'', as well as [[William Shakespeare|Shakespeare]] plays.<ref name="Scott 2021">{{cite web |last=Scott |first=Jason |title=Teddy Swims: Rags to Riches |url=https://americansongwriter.com/teddy-swims-rags-to-riches/ |website=American Songwriter |access-date=May 7, 2022 |date=August 16, 2021}}</ref> He began playing instruments including piano and [[ukulele]], and watched YouTube videos of singers to help develop his vocal technique.<ref name="Freeman 2021" /><ref name="Neunan 2022" />

